        "text": "CHAD ",
        "text_level": 1,
        "page_idx": 2
    },
    {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "FIFTH REVIEW UNDER THE EXTENDED CREDIT FACILITY ARRANGEMENT AND FINANCING ASSURANCES REVIEW ",
        "text_level": 1,
        "page_idx": 2
    },
    {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "KEY ISSUES ",
        "text_level": 1,
        "page_idx": 2
    },
    {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "Context. Non-oil economic activity is recovering slowly, with non-oil growth projected to increase to 2 percent in 2019, from 0.5 percent in 2018. Fiscal consolidation is in line with program objectives and the debt position is improving. The security situation and social conditions remain difficult. Parliamentary elections are expected in early 2020. The reform momentum is progressing slowly, hampered by weak administrative capacity and fragility. ",
        "page_idx": 2
    },
    {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "Program performance. All end-June quantitative performance criteria (QPCs) and the indicative target (IT) on social spending have been met. Of the five structural benchmarks (SBs) due by end-September, two were met, one was completed in October, and progress has been made on the two outstanding. One SB due by end-November is proposed to be reset to end-December 2019. The program is supported by CEMAC-wide efforts to maintain an appropriate monetary policy stance, build up regional reserves, and promote financial sector stability. ",
        "page_idx": 2
    },
    {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "Key policy recommendations. Staff urged the authorities to: (i) submit a draft 2020 budget to the National Assembly in line with their commitments under the program, (ii) continue efforts to increase non-oil revenue, especially through improvements in the tax and customs administrations, (iii) intensify efforts to ensure that the end-year social spending target is met, (iv) strengthen debt management and refrain from contracting non-concessional borrowing, (v) adopt restructuring and funding plans for the two public banks, and (vi) continue to strengthen the anti-corruption framework. ",
        "page_idx": 2
    },
    {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "Staff views. Staff supports the completion of the fifth review under the ECF arrangement, given ChadÔÇÖs broadly satisfactory performance and commitment to the program despite significant challenges. Completion of the fifth review will result in the disbursement of SDR 28.04 million. The Fund arrangement remains instrumental to catalyze donor support and address ChadÔÇÖs protracted balance of payment needs. The main downside risks to the program include rising insecurity, a drop in oil prices, fiscal slippages in the run-up to the elections, and further deterioration in the position of public banks. The upside risks mostly consist of higher oil revenues. ",
        "page_idx": 2
    },
    {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "Discussions started at the margins of the Annual Meetings and then continued in NÔÇÖDjamena during October 24-November 5. The staff team comprised Mr. E. Gemayel (head), Messrs. M. Ben Hassine and M. Ahmed, Ms. A. Viseth (all AFR), Mr. R. Green (SPR), Mr. J. Ntamatungiro (Resident Representative) and Mr. B. Topeur (local economist). Mr. Bangrim Kibassim (OED) joined the mission. Staff of the BEAC and the World Bank attended some of the policy meetings. Meetings were held with Mr. Kabadi, President of the National Assembly, Mr. Nguilin, Minister of Finance and Budget, Mr. Doubragne, Minister of Economy and Development Planning, Mr. Koua, Minister of Oil, Energy and Mines, Mr. Mahamat Hassan, National Director of the BEAC, and other senior officials, as well as representatives of the private sector, civil society, and international development partners. A press conference was held at the end of the mission and a press release was issued. Ms. M. Ndiguimbaye assisted the mission in NÔÇÖDjamena and Ms. V. Pilouzoue and Ms. N. Margevich supported the preparation of the staff report. ",
        "page_idx": 3
    },
